metadata.name: Miniscapes #287
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: a house divided #48
metadata.description:
This piece reuses the same line drawing algorithm from 'this is where i draw the line', meant to emulate a marker drawing on paper.

In terms of composition, we start with a single square, which we divide into two rectangles, either horizontally or vertically. We then repeat this process some number of times for each of the resulting rectangles. Finally, we fill the rectangles by drawing them with lines. These lines
can be either straight or curved.

The collection of inks and papers has also been expanded from 'this is where i draw the line'. Collectors of that piece have been placed on the reserve list as a thank you for their support.

This piece was created using p5.js

metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #82
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Obliques #125
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: fREEDOM PUNK #1
metadata.description:
Welcome to fREEDOM PUNK world.
This project is Image Composition Layers pngs.
Created with 128x128 px format.
There are 9 Layers in this project. (included transparent png files)
- Background > 130 different images
- Body > 12 different body colors.
- Eyes > 24 different eyes.
- Nose > 13 different noses.
- Mouth > 58 different mouths.
- Eyeglasses > 19 different eyeglasses. (chance of nothing is much higher)
- Hair > 133 different hair-styles and headwear.
- Cloth > 160 different clothes.
- Things (In front of the punk) > 60 different things. (chance of nothing is much higher)

So you can generate your unique fREEDOM PUNKs for sure, due to very high possibilities by the layers.

Enjoy and good luck!

metadata.name: Petri 1500 v2 QHD  #757
metadata.description:
Petri 1500 is a celebration of reaching 1500 Twitter followers.
As I've grown as an artist what represents that growth but a petri dish, filled with life, finding a way.

There is a bug in the original version that cause display issues on retina & QHD displays. So this version fixes that, is free to all that held a copy at 00:30 14-09-2022 and a few spares for luck.

A sillybration of all things fx(hash) featuring some of my recognisable pallets and primatives
along with something new to me - noise and 'realistic' nature sketches.
All mashed for pure fun.

L to download 1000x1000
S to download 4000x4000
H to download 8000x8000

metadata.name: Achromatic Neutral #1
metadata.description:
In this piece I tried to explore the combinations of neutral colors in this abstract generative piece. Nothing better than mixing AI + Generative art.

I felt inspired to create this piece after reading this quote from Arshile Gorky,

‚ÄúAbstraction allows man to see with his mind what he cannot see physically with his eyes....Abstract art enables the artist to perceive beyond the tangible, to extract the infinite out of the finite. It is the emancipation of the mind. It is an exploration into unknown areas.‚Äù

I hope you like it! :D

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 2 #442
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.
